          <div
              
                style="padding-bottom:66.95999908447266%;"
              
              class="
                image-block-wrapper
                
          
        
                has-aspect-ratio
              "
              data-animation-role="image"
              
  data-animation-override

          >
            <noscript><img src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490318632579-E1I5SCLHL4X9MCFVO1RU/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kPhE_b-FKx_EcxRx4teFEVN7gQa3H78H3Y0txjaiv_0fDoOvxcdMmMKkDsyUqMSsMWxHk725yiiHCCLfrh8O1z4YTzHvnKhyp6Da-NYroOW3ZGjoBKy3azqku80C789l0k5fwC0WRNFJBIXiBeNI5fL8LmMajxsBXeYxVzkYts3ds68Ud4HgM4ArFxmxGpI5hQ/image-asset.jpeg" alt="Close up of Qingjin High Mountain Oolong rolled into pea size round balls." /></noscript><img class="thumb-image" data-src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490318632579-E1I5SCLHL4X9MCFVO1RU/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kPhE_b-FKx_EcxRx4teFEVN7gQa3H78H3Y0txjaiv_0fDoOvxcdMmMKkDsyUqMSsMWxHk725yiiHCCLfrh8O1z4YTzHvnKhyp6Da-NYroOW3ZGjoBKy3azqku80C789l0k5fwC0WRNFJBIXiBeNI5fL8LmMajxsBXeYxVzkYts3ds68Ud4HgM4ArFxmxGpI5hQ/image-asset.jpeg" data-image="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490318632579-E1I5SCLHL4X9MCFVO1RU/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kPhE_b-FKx_EcxRx4teFEVN7gQa3H78H3Y0txjaiv_0fDoOvxcdMmMKkDsyUqMSsMWxHk725yiiHCCLfrh8O1z4YTzHvnKhyp6Da-NYroOW3ZGjoBKy3azqku80C789l0k5fwC0WRNFJBIXiBeNI5fL8LmMajxsBXeYxVzkYts3ds68Ud4HgM4ArFxmxGpI5hQ/image-asset.jpeg" data-image-dimensions="2500x1674" data-image-focal-point="0.5,0.5" alt="Close up of Qingjin High Mountain Oolong rolled into pea size round balls." data-load="false" data-image-id="58d475278419c2d3807617ee" data-type="image" />
          </div>
        
          
        

        
          
          <figcaption class="image-caption-wrapper">
            <div class="image-caption"><p>Close up of Qingjin High Mountain Oolong rolled into pea size round balls.</p></div>
          </figcaption>
        
      
        </figure>
      

    </div>
  


  


</div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1490318458710_23468"><div class="sqs-block-content"><h3>MEDIUM QINGJIN HIGH MOUNTAIN OOLONG 40 GRAMS</h3><p>Mr. Chen and his family moved to Ren’ai to start their tea farming life in 1980s. Nowadays, the second generations run the family farms while Mr. Chen teaches them the ins and outs of tea making. Spring time in April is their busiest time as they make teas 24-7 as they are picked. Their land is rented from the local indigenous family. This tea in coffee terms is easy drinking with medium body. An everyday stable.</p><p>Tasting Notes: A 35% oxidized oolong with smooth nutty jasmine aromas, medium boldness and enjoyable umami sweet after taste. Breath through nose and release through mouth to enhance the tasting! &nbsp;<br />Brewing: 3 grams, 95C, 150ml, 3 brews, 1-5 minutes<br />Varietal: Qingxin oolong<br />Elevation: 1200 m<br />Date: 2016 Spring</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block image-block sqs-block-image" data-block-type="5" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1490318458710_26828"><div class="sqs-block-content">








  

    
  
    <div
        class="
          image-block-outer-wrapper
          layout-caption-below
          design-layout-inline
          
          
          
