            <noscript><img src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490305621479-CEG3RQA9Z1AU8JX2IUBN/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kHKhAb3gAe5BZt80QwntQK1Zw-zPPgdn4jUwVcJE1ZvWEtT5uBSRWt4vQZAgTJucoTqqXjS3CfNDSuuf31e0tVFVouPNGfZ4tqfBqWgeWeaZP_jGvPfqCw51UI88WSNm13NscEGw-uMOR3YLbrLt4JY/image-asset.jpeg" alt="View of Pinglin mountain range in north east of Taipei." /></noscript><img class="thumb-image" data-src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490305621479-CEG3RQA9Z1AU8JX2IUBN/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kHKhAb3gAe5BZt80QwntQK1Zw-zPPgdn4jUwVcJE1ZvWEtT5uBSRWt4vQZAgTJucoTqqXjS3CfNDSuuf31e0tVFVouPNGfZ4tqfBqWgeWeaZP_jGvPfqCw51UI88WSNm13NscEGw-uMOR3YLbrLt4JY/image-asset.jpeg" data-image="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54028565e4b079634bac0558/1490305621479-CEG3RQA9Z1AU8JX2IUBN/ke17ZwdGBToddI8pDm48kHKhAb3gAe5BZt80QwntQK1Zw-zPPgdn4jUwVcJE1ZvWEtT5uBSRWt4vQZAgTJucoTqqXjS3CfNDSuuf31e0tVFVouPNGfZ4tqfBqWgeWeaZP_jGvPfqCw51UI88WSNm13NscEGw-uMOR3YLbrLt4JY/image-asset.jpeg" data-image-dimensions="449x302" data-image-focal-point="0.5,0.5" alt="View of Pinglin mountain range in north east of Taipei." data-load="false" data-image-id="58d44255893fc0bdd134eb19" data-type="image" />
          </div>
        
          
        

        
          
          <figcaption class="image-caption-wrapper">
            <div class="image-caption"><p>View of Pinglin mountain range in north east of Taipei.</p></div>
          </figcaption>
        
      
        </figure>
      

    </div>
  


  


</div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1490071600107_288671"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p>This month we are exploring one of Taiwan’s oldest tea regions –The Pinglin District. The district is the mountainous part of the New Taipei City. Pinglin has been producing the infamous flower tea- Pouchong oolong- since 1880s. The area is an environmentally protected area because the nearby rivers supply water to northern Taiwan therefore no developments are permitted which creates a protected tea farming environment till this day. Pouchong simply means “the wrapped kind” because back in the day, the teas are wrapped into paper square packages during its drying process. The method and tea growing was transferred from Fujian. This month, we are exploring the less famous, yet still tasty, rare teas from Pinglin.&nbsp;<br />This month, instead of 40g of 2 teas, we are exploring 3 teas of 25-30g each. &nbsp;</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block image-block sqs-block-image" data-block-type="5" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1490071600107_292039"><div class="sqs-block-content">








  

    
  
    <div
        class="
          image-block-outer-wrapper
          layout-caption-below
          design-layout-inline
          
          
          
